        "description": "Visualforce controller that overrides the standard Contact delete action to enforce NPSP-specific cleanup rules. If the Contact has Closed/Won Opportunities or Organization Opportunities and is not the last person in the Household, deletion is blocked. If the Contact is the last member in a Household or One-to-One Account, NPSP prompts the user to either delete the Contact and leave the Account in place, or delete both the Contact and the Account together. The controller cascade-deletes related Opportunities (when the Contact is the Primary Contact), Recurring Donations, and Relationships. This override applies only to manual deletions via the UI; API-based or bulk deletions do not go through this flow. The source code This controller separates the delete flow into three distinct paths based on runtime context: if the Contact is not the last member of an individual account, `deleteContact()` cascade-deletes its Opportunities and Recurring Donations and then removes the Contact; if the Contact is the last member and the user chose to leave the account, `deleteContactOnly()` runs the same contact-and-child deletion without touching the account; and if the user chose to delete both, `deleteAccount()` runs the cascade delete framework against the entire Account. Each path validates permissions individually using `UTIL_Permissions.canDelete()` with a thrown `InsufficientPermissionException` on failure, and the inner `CascadeDeleteException` type is thrown when related Closed/Won Opportunities or open Cases block deletion. The controller distinguishes Lightning Experience from Classic via `UserInfo.getUiThemeDisplayed().contains('Theme4')` and sets the `sforceNav` variable to either `'back'` or `'home'` accordingly, enabling the VF page's JavaScript to issue the correct LEX navigation call post-delete."
