        "description": "Validator class that checks Household Naming Settings for correctness before they are saved in NPSP Settings > People > Households. It validates the custom implementing class reference (if an admin has configured a custom Apex-based naming override), the name format strings (such as `{!{!FirstName}} {!LastName} Household`), and all field API name references within format strings, catching errors before they cause runtime failures in household name generation. Custom implementing classes must implement all methods in the Household naming interface. The validator returns structured error messages that the NPSP Settings UI displays to administrators. The source code This validator uses Apex's `Type.forName(className)` and `classType.newInstance()` reflective APIs to instantiate the admin-configured implementing class at validation time, then invokes `getExampleName()` against a two-contact sample household to smoke-test the format string before it is persisted. The reflective instantiation approach means validation only catches runtime exceptions from the naming engine, not compile-time issues like missing methods; a custom class that compiles but throws a `StringException` on certain name patterns would pass validation if the example contacts do not trigger that branch. Format field validation covers all three name strings (`Household_Name_Format__c`, `Formal_Greeting_Format__c`, `Informal_Greeting_Format__c`) independently, so a format that works for the name but fails for the greeting will still be caught. Errors are accumulated in a `Notification` value object rather than thrown, allowing the caller to display all errors at once rather than stopping at the first failure."
